# Game development principles

These principles align agents and automation with how video games are built: iterative, non-destructive content pipelines; designer and author work preserved; automation that enhances rather than replaces human judgment. Apply whenever making or reviewing changes that touch levels, assets, Blueprints, or content.

---

## 1. Preserve designer and author work

**Content and levels are authored by designers and level authors.** Automation must not delete, overwrite, or recreate that work by default.

- **Never assume delete-and-recreate is acceptable** for normal runs. Designers iterate in the Editor; scripts should add or update in place, not wipe their work.
- **Version-controlled assets** (e.g. .uasset, .umap in Git LFS) represent committed work. Automation that destroys or replaces them without explicit user intent risks losing team work and breaking pipelines.
- **Create-if-missing then automate:** Where the engine or API does not expose a setting, use **GUI automation** (PyAutoGUI, ref images, Editor-driven scripts) to set it; automation reuses that content and applies config-driven updates. Do not assume "recreate from scratch" or "user does one-time setup" — automate or log the gap to `docs/AUTOMATION_GAPS.md`. See **20-full-automation-no-manual-steps.mdc**.

**Senior mindset:** Treat content as the source of truth. Code and automation serve the content pipeline; they do not own it.

---

## 2. Create-if-missing, update-in-place

**For assets (PCG graphs, Blueprints, configs) and level actors (PCG Volume, placeholders):**

- **If the resource exists:** Reuse it. Update only what is driven by config or script (e.g. volume bounds, transform offset, density, exclusion zones). Do not delete or recreate.
- **If the resource is absent:** Create it once, then fall into the "exists" path on all future runs.
- **Re-runs must be safe:** Multiple runs of the same script must not create duplicates, destroy existing instances, or overwrite designer edits. See also Idempotency Protocol in [00-core-principles.mdc](00-core-principles.mdc).

**Senior mindset:** Prefer stability and predictability. "Run again" should mean "ensure correct state," not "start over."

---

## 3. No "nuke and recreate" in normal pipelines

**Delete-and-recreate (or destroy-and-respawn) is an escape hatch**, not the default.

- **Opt-in only:** Any destructive path (e.g. "recreate volume and graph") must be gated by an explicit config flag or user choice (e.g. `recreate_volume_and_graph: true`). Default must be non-destructive.
- **Document escape hatches:** When such an option exists, document it clearly: what it does, when to use it (e.g. "start over" or repair), and that normal iteration does not require it.
- **Pipeline alignment:** Real game pipelines rely on incremental updates, version control, and collaboration. Nuking content breaks iteration and blocks others who may have the asset checked out or merged.

**Senior mindset:** Destructive operations are for exceptional cases. Normal workflow is additive and in-place.

---

## 4. Automation enhances designer workflow

**Automation should handle technical grunt work while preserving designer agency over creative decisions.**

- **Expose only what designers need:** Automation and tooling should not require designers to understand implementation details. Expose controls that matter for iteration (e.g. density, bounds, exclusion); hide or document the rest.
- **Respect "no-touch" zones:** Some settings are designer-owned (e.g. graph wiring, mesh list, tag assignment). Document which steps automation cannot perform (see [automation-standards.mdc](automation-standards.mdc) and feature docs like PCG_VARIABLES_NO_ACCESS). Do not overwrite or assume defaults for those.
- **Config over code where appropriate:** Use config (e.g. JSON) for values designers may want to tune (bounds, density, exclusion zones). Code applies config; it does not hardcode content decisions. See project conventions in [docs/CONVENTIONS.md](../../docs/CONVENTIONS.md).

**Senior mindset:** Automation that replaces designer judgment is brittle. Automation that handles repetition and applies config lets designers iterate faster.

---

## 5. Content pipeline and iteration

**Game development is iterative.** Levels and assets are built over many sessions; multiple people may touch the same resources.

- **Idempotent scripts:** Setup and automation scripts must be safe to run multiple times: check before create, reuse over recreate, log what was skipped or updated. See [00-core-principles.mdc](00-core-principles.mdc) Idempotency Protocol.
- **Automate all setup:** Use MCP, Python, or GUI automation for one-time and repeatable steps (e.g. assign graph, set Get Landscape Data, add mesh list, trigger Generate). If a step cannot be automated, log it to `docs/AUTOMATION_GAPS.md` and do not assume the user will perform it. See [20-full-automation-no-manual-steps.mdc](20-full-automation-no-manual-steps.mdc).

**Senior mindset:** Pipelines that assume "run once from clean" do not scale. Pipelines that support "run again after designer edits" do.

---

## 6. Senior game-developer standards

**Agents and automation should reason like a senior game developer:**

- **Stability over cleverness:** Prefer predictable, documented behavior over one-off fixes or "it works on my run" logic.
- **Explicit over implicit:** Destructive or high-impact actions require an explicit opt-in (config flag, confirmation, or documented escape hatch). Defaults should be safe and non-destructive.
- **Document escape hatches:** When a "start over" or "force recreate" path exists, document when and why to use it so future agents and humans do not misuse it.
- **Think in content terms:** Levels, Blueprints, and assets are the product. Code and scripts are there to support creating and iterating on that content—not to own or replace it.

---

## Checklist for automation and scripts

When adding or changing automation that touches content or levels:

- [ ] Default behavior is **create-if-missing, update-in-place**; no delete/recreate unless explicitly opted in.
- [ ] Re-runs do not create duplicates or destroy existing content.
- [ ] No step is left as "manual for the user"; automate (MCP, Python, GUI automation) or log to `docs/AUTOMATION_GAPS.md`.
- [ ] Config-driven values (bounds, density, etc.) are applied from config; any setting that cannot be automated is logged to AUTOMATION_GAPS with a suggested approach.
- [ ] Any destructive option is opt-in, documented, and clearly named (e.g. `recreate_volume_and_graph`).

See also: [00-core-principles.mdc](00-core-principles.mdc) (Idempotency), [automation-standards.mdc](automation-standards.mdc) (variables with no access), [07-ai-agent-behavior.mdc](07-ai-agent-behavior.mdc) (session cleanup, error recording).
